<rss xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" version="2.0"><channel><title>React - Tag - TyrangYang_Blog</title><link>https://tyrangyang.github.io/TyrangYang_blog/tags/react/</link><description>React - Tag - TyrangYang_Blog</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Sun, 12 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://tyrangyang.github.io/TyrangYang_blog/tags/react/" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Understanding React Fiber - Trees, Diff, and Commit Phases</title><link>https://tyrangyang.github.io/TyrangYang_blog/react-fiber/</link><pubDate>Sun, 12 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><author>Haolin Yang</author><guid>https://tyrangyang.github.io/TyrangYang_blog/react-fiber/</guid><description><![CDATA[<h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>
<p>React Fiber is the core of modern React rendering, enabling <strong>incremental rendering, time slicing, and high-performance updates</strong>. In this blog, we will explore:</p>
<ul>
<li>Fiber nodes and structure</li>
<li>Fiber loop and traversal</li>
<li>Diff/reconciliation algorithm</li>
<li>Work-in-progress (WIP) tree</li>
<li>Current fiber tree vs real DOM</li>
<li>Commit phase and tree flow</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id="1-what-is-a-fiber-node">1. What is a Fiber Node?</h2>
<p>A <strong>Fiber node</strong> is a unit of work in React‚Äôs incremental rendering. It contains:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>type</code> ‚Üí element type (<code>div</code>, <code>span</code>, Component)</li>
<li><code>key</code> ‚Üí unique identifier for list reconciliation</li>
<li><code>props</code> ‚Üí element properties</li>
<li><code>stateNode</code> ‚Üí reference to actual DOM node or component instance</li>
<li><code>child</code>, <code>sibling</code>, <code>return</code> ‚Üí pointers for tree traversal</li>
<li><code>alternate</code> ‚Üí link to the previous fiber (used for diffing)</li>
<li><code>effectTag</code> ‚Üí indicates updates needed (<code>Placement</code>, <code>Update</code>, <code>Deletion</code>)</li>
</ul>
